               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18451027-name-1217" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1217" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1217" type="surname" value="SPARLING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1217" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY SPARLING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to William Buddry Elsden, of Bruns<lb></lb>wick-place, Old Kent-road. On the 30th of Sept. this piece of printed cotton was safe in the shop at ten minutes past eight o'clock—it was missed at half-past eight—I am quite sure this is it—it is my master's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18451027-name-1218" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1218" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1218" type="surname" value="NOAKES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1218" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM NOAKES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 104.) On the evening of the 30th of Sept., at twenty minutes past eight o'clock, I stopped the prisoner about 300 yards from the prosecutor's—I asked what he had got—he said, "Nothing"—I opened his coat, and found this cotton under it—I said, "Do you call this nothing?"—he said, "That is what I just picked up."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I picked it up against the Railway station.</p>
